snippet.textDisplay:
"Basically no drawback"
Eh... yeah, good cause and all... but if you leave this on all year, you can easily add hundreds of dollars/euros to your power bill. US power prices look to be a bit lower, but here in the Netherlands you pay about €0.22 per KWh. Which comes out to if you leave a device running 24/7, it will cost you its wattage times two in euros.
As I said it is indeed for a good cause, but I think people should be aware of this. If I leave this on all the time in a year that's basically a 2070 super I've donated to them (and I'm still making do with a 1060).

snippet.textDisplay:
Hello! from Romania :) I think FOLDING @ HOME was running on my computer back in 2004-9 when I was in university. Sounds really familiar to me. And imagine bandwidth and computing power back then! :)) But it was a joy to see single-core CPUs working hard in half of the guy's rooms in the uni's campus. So to give you a perspective: all we had were Athlons and Semprons from AMD (girls's rooms had older PCs with K6 processors configs :P )

[ Athlon (Slot A) (Argon, Pluto/Orion, Thunderbird) (1999)
Athlon (Socket A) (Thunderbird) (2000)
Duron (Spitfire, Morgan, Applebred) (2000) ]
and
Intel's Pentium III with freq not more then 1,4 GHz :))

Ooo what times for shared protein folding calculations :P
